exercises.name: 3/4 Sit-Up
exercises.hint: Lie down on the floor and secure your feet. Your legs should be bent at the knees.

exercises.name: 90/90 Hamstring
exercises.hint: Lie on your back, with one leg extended straight out.

exercises.name: Ab Crunch Machine
exercises.hint: Select a light resistance and sit down on the ab machine placing your feet under the pads provided and grabbing the top handles. Your arms should be bent at a 90 degree angle as you rest the triceps on the pads provided. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Ab Roller
exercises.hint: Hold the Ab Roller with both hands and kneel on the floor.

exercises.name: Adductor
exercises.hint: Lie face down with one leg on a foam roll.

exercises.name: Adductor/Groin
exercises.hint: Lie on your back with your feet raised towards the ceiling.

exercises.name: Advanced Kettlebell Windmill
exercises.hint: Clean and press a kettlebell overhead with one arm.

exercises.name: Air Bike
exercises.hint: Lie flat on the floor with your lower back pressed to the ground. For this exercise, you will need to put your hands beside your head. Be careful however to not strain with the neck as you perform it. Now lift your shoulders into the crunch position.

exercises.name: All Fours Quad Stretch
exercises.hint: Start off on your hands and knees, then lift your leg off the floor and hold the foot with your hand.

exercises.name: Alternate Hammer Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright and a dumbbell in each hand being held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso.

exercises.name: Alternate Heel Touchers
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor with the knees bent and the feet on the floor around 18-24 inches apart. Your arms should be extended by your side. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Alternate Incline Dumbbell Curl
exercises.hint: Sit down on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand being held at arms length. Tip: Keep the elbows close to the torso.This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Alternate Leg Diagonal Bound
exercises.hint: Assume a comfortable stance with one foot slightly in front of the other.

exercises.name: Alternating Cable Shoulder Press
exercises.hint: Move the cables to the bottom of the tower and select an appropriate weight.

exercises.name: Alternating Deltoid Raise
exercises.hint: In a standing position, hold a pair of dumbbells at your side.

exercises.name: Alternating Floor Press
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor with two kettlebells next to your shoulders.

exercises.name: Alternating Hang Clean
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells between your feet. To get in the starting position, push your butt back and look straight ahead.

exercises.name: Alternating Kettlebell Press
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders. Clean the kettlebells to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you pull the kettlebells towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrists as you do so.

exercises.name: Alternating Kettlebell Row
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells in front of your feet. Bend your knees slightly and push your butt out as much as possible. As you bend over to get into the starting position grab both kettlebells by the handles.

exercises.name: Alternating Renegade Row
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells on the floor about shoulder width apart. Position yourself on your toes and your hands as though you were doing a pushup, with the body straight and extended. Use the handles of the kettlebells to support your upper body. You may need to position your feet wide for support.

exercises.name: Ankle On The Knee
exercises.hint: From a lying position, bend your knees and keep your feet on the floor.

exercises.name: Anterior Tibialis-SMR
exercises.hint: Begin seated on the ground with your legs bent and your feet on the floor.

exercises.name: Anti-Gravity Press
exercises.hint: Place a bar on the ground behind the head of an incline bench.

exercises.name: Arm Circles
exercises.hint: Stand up and extend your arms straight out by the sides. The arms should be parallel to the floor and perpendicular (90-degree angle) to your torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Arnold Dumbbell Press
exercises.hint: Sit on an exercise bench with back support and hold two dumbbells in front of you at about upper chest level with your palms facing your body and your elbows bent. Tip: Your arms should be next to your torso. The starting position should look like the contracted portion of a dumbbell curl.

exercises.name: Around The Worlds
exercises.hint: Lay down on a flat bench holding a dumbbell in each hand with the palms of the hands facing towards the ceiling. Tip: Your arms should be parallel to the floor and next to your thighs. To avoid injury, make sure that you keep your elbows slightly bent. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Atlas Stone Trainer
exercises.hint: This trainer is effective for developing Atlas Stone strength for those who don't have access to stones, and are typically made from bar ends or heavy pipe.

exercises.name: Atlas Stones
exercises.hint: Begin with the atlas stone between your feet. Bend at the hips to wrap your arms vertically around the Atlas Stone, attempting to get your fingers underneath the stone. Many stones will have a small flat portion on the bottom, which will make the stone easier to hold.

exercises.name: Axle Deadlift
exercises.hint: Approach the bar so that it is centered over your feet. You feet should be about hip width apart. Bend at the hip to grip the bar at shoulder width, allowing your shoulder blades to protract. Typically, you would use an over/under grip.

exercises.name: Back Flyes - With Bands
exercises.hint: Run a band around a stationary post like that of a squat rack.

exercises.name: Backward Drag
exercises.hint: Load a sled with the desired weight, attaching a rope or straps to the sled that you can hold onto.

exercises.name: Backward Medicine Ball Throw
exercises.hint: This exercise is best done with a partner. If you lack a partner, the ball can be thrown and retrieved or thrown against a wall.

exercises.name: Balance Board
exercises.hint: Place a balance board in front of you.

exercises.name: Ball Leg Curl
exercises.hint: Begin on the floor laying on your back with your feet on top of the ball.

exercises.name: Band Assisted Pull-Up
exercises.hint: Choke the band around the center of the pullup bar. You can use different bands to provide varying levels of assistance.

exercises.name: Band Good Morning
exercises.hint: Using a 41 inch band, stand on one end, spreading your feet a small amount. Bend at the hips to loop the end of the band behind your neck. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Band Good Morning (Pull Through)
exercises.hint: Loop the band around a post. Standing a little ways away, loop the opposite end around the neck. Your hands can help hold the band in position.

exercises.name: Band Hip Adductions
exercises.hint: Anchor a band around a solid post or other object.

exercises.name: Band Pull Apart
exercises.hint: Begin with your arms extended straight out in front of you, holding the band with both hands.

exercises.name: Band Skull Crusher
exercises.hint: Secure a band to the base of a rack or the bench. Lay on the bench so that the band is lined up with your head.

exercises.name: Barbell Ab Rollout
exercises.hint: For this exercise you will need to get into a pushup position, but instead of having your hands of the floor, you will be grabbing on to an Olympic barbell (loaded with 5-10 lbs on each side) instead. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Ab Rollout - On Knees
exercises.hint: Hold an Olympic barbell loaded with 5-10lbs on each side and kneel on the floor.

exercises.name: Barbell Bench Press - Medium Grip
exercises.hint: Lie back on a flat bench. Using a medium width grip (a grip that creates a 90-degree angle in the middle of the movement between the forearms and the upper arms), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright while holding a barbell at a shoulder-width grip. The palm of your hands should be facing forward and the elbows should be close to the torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Curls Lying Against An Incline
exercises.hint: Lie against an incline bench, with your arms holding a barbell and hanging down in a horizontal line. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Deadlift
exercises.hint: Stand in front of a loaded barbell.

exercises.name: Barbell Full Squat
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack just above shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.

exercises.name: Barbell Glute Bridge
exercises.hint: Begin seated on the ground with a loaded barbell over your legs. Using a fat bar or having a pad on the bar can greatly reduce the discomfort caused by this exercise. Roll the bar so that it is directly above your hips, and lay down flat on the floor.

exercises.name: Barbell Guillotine Bench Press
exercises.hint: Using a medium width grip (a grip that creates a 90-degree angle in the middle of the movement between the forearms and the upper arms), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over your neck with your arms locked. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Hack Squat
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a barbell behind you at arms length and your feet at shoulder width. Tip: A shoulder width grip is best with the palms of your hands facing back. You can use wrist wraps for this exercise for a better grip. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Hip Thrust
exercises.hint: Begin seated on the ground with a bench directly behind you. Have a loaded barbell over your legs. Using a fat bar or having a pad on the bar can greatly reduce the discomfort caused by this exercise.

exercises.name: Barbell Incline Bench Press - Medium Grip
exercises.hint: Lie back on an incline bench. Using a medium-width grip (a grip that creates a 90-degree angle in the middle of the movement between the forearms and the upper arms), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Incline Shoulder Raise
exercises.hint: Lie back on an Incline Bench. Using a medium width grip (a grip that is slightly wider than shoulder width), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Lunge
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack just below shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.

exercises.name: Barbell Rear Delt Row
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a barbell using a wide (higher than shoulder width) and overhand (palms facing your body) grip.

exercises.name: Barbell Rollout from Bench
exercises.hint: Place a loaded barbell on the ground, near the end of a bench. Kneel with both legs on the bench, and take a medium to narrow grip on the barbell. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Seated Calf Raise
exercises.hint: Place a block about 12 inches in front of a flat bench.

exercises.name: Barbell Shoulder Press
exercises.hint: Sit on a bench with back support in a squat rack. Position a barbell at a height that is just above your head. Grab the barbell with a pronated grip (palms facing forward).

exercises.name: Barbell Shrug
exercises.hint: Stand up straight with your feet at shoulder width as you hold a barbell with both hands in front of you using a pronated grip (palms facing the thighs). Tip: Your hands should be a little wider than shoulder width apart. You can use wrist wraps for this exercise for a better grip. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Shrug Behind The Back
exercises.hint: Stand up straight with your feet at shoulder width as you hold a barbell with both hands behind your back using a pronated grip (palms facing back). Tip: Your hands should be a little wider than shoulder width apart. You can use wrist wraps for this exercise for better grip. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Side Bend
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a barbell placed on the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck). Your feet should be shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Side Split Squat
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a barbell placed on the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck). Your feet should be placed wide apart with the foot of the lead leg angled out to the side. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Squat
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack to just below shoulder level. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.

exercises.name: Barbell Step Ups
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a barbell placed on the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) and stand upright behind an elevated platform (such as the one used for spotting behind a flat bench). This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Barbell Walking Lunge
exercises.hint: Begin standing with your feet shoulder width apart and a barbell across your upper back.

exercises.name: Battling Ropes
exercises.hint: For this exercise you will need a heavy rope anchored at its center 15-20 feet away. Standing in front of the rope, take an end in each hand with your arms extended at your side. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bear Crawl Sled Drags
exercises.hint: Wearing either a harness or a loose weight belt, attach the chain to the back so that you will be facing away from the sled. Bend down so that your hands are on the ground. Your back should be flat and knees bent. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Behind Head Chest Stretch
exercises.hint: Sit upright on the floor with your partner behind you.

exercises.name: Bench Dips
exercises.hint: For this exercise you will need to place a bench behind your back. With the bench perpendicular to your body, and while looking away from it, hold on to the bench on its edge with the hands fully extended, separated at shoulder width. The legs will be extended forward, bent at the waist and perpendicular to your torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bench Jump
exercises.hint: Begin with a box or bench 1-2 feet in front of you. Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bench Press - Powerlifting
exercises.hint: Begin by lying on the bench, getting your head beyond the bar if possible. Tuck your feet underneath you and arch your back. Using the bar to help support your weight, lift your shoulder off the bench and retract them, squeezing the shoulder blades together. Use your feet to drive your traps into the bench. Maintain this tight body position throughout the movement.

exercises.name: Bench Press with Chains
exercises.hint: Adjust the leader chain, shortening it to the desired length.Place the chains on the sleeves of the bar.

exercises.name: Bench Sprint
exercises.hint: Stand on the ground with one foot resting on a bench or box with your heel close to the edge.

exercises.name: Bent-Arm Barbell Pullover
exercises.hint: Lie on a flat bench with a barbell using a shoulder grip width.

exercises.name: Bent-Arm Dumbbell Pullover
exercises.hint: Place a dumbbell standing up on a flat bench.

exercises.name: Bent-Knee Hip Raise
exercises.hint: Lay flat on the floor with your arms next to your sides.

exercises.name: Bent Over Barbell Row
exercises.hint: Holding a barbell with a pronated grip (palms facing down), bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward, by bending at the waist, while keeping the back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Tip: Make sure that you keep the head up. The barbell should hang directly in front of you as your arms hang perpendicular to the floor and your torso. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Bent Over Dumbbell Rear Delt Raise With Head On Bench
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell in each hand and with an incline bench in front of you.

exercises.name: Bent Over Low-Pulley Side Lateral
exercises.hint: Select a weight and hold the handle of the low pulley with your right hand.

exercises.name: Bent Over One-Arm Long Bar Row
exercises.hint: Put weight on one of the ends of an Olympic barbell. Make sure that you either place the other end of the barbell in the corner of two walls; or put a heavy object on the ground so the barbell cannot slide backward.

exercises.name: Bent Over Two-Arm Long Bar Row
exercises.hint: Put weight on one of the ends of an Olympic barbell. Make sure that you either place the other end of the barbell in the corner of two walls; or put a heavy object on the ground so the barbell cannot slide backward.

exercises.name: Bent Over Two-Dumbbell Row
exercises.hint: With a dumbbell in each hand (palms facing your torso), bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward by bending at the waist; as you bend make sure to keep your back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Tip: Make sure that you keep the head up. The weights should hang directly in front of you as your arms hang perpendicular to the floor and your torso. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Bent Over Two-Dumbbell Row With Palms In
exercises.hint: With a dumbbell in each hand (palms facing each other), bend your knees slightly and bring your torso forward, by bending at the waist, while keeping the back straight until it is almost parallel to the floor. Tip: Make sure that you keep the head up. The weights should hang directly in front of you as your arms hang perpendicular to the floor and your torso. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Bent Press
exercises.hint: Clean a kettlebell to your shoulder. Clean the kettlebell to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you raise the kettlebell towards your shoulder. The wrist should rotate as you do so. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bicycling, Stationary
exercises.hint: To begin, seat yourself on the bike and adjust the seat to your height.

exercises.name: Board Press
exercises.hint: Begin by lying on the bench, getting your head beyond the bar if possible. One to five boards, made out of 2x6's, can be screwed together and held in place by a training partner, bands, or just tucked under your shirt.

exercises.name: Body Tricep Press
exercises.hint: Position a bar in a rack at chest height.

exercises.name: Body-Up
exercises.hint: Assume a plank position on the ground. You should be supporting your bodyweight on your toes and forearms, keeping your torso straight. Your forearms should be shoulder-width apart. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bodyweight Flyes
exercises.hint: Position two equally loaded EZ bars on the ground next to each other. Ensure they are able to roll.

exercises.name: Bodyweight Mid Row
exercises.hint: Begin by taking a medium to wide grip on a pull-up apparatus with your palms facing away from you. From a hanging position, tuck your knees to your chest, leaning back and getting your legs over your side of the pull-up apparatus. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bodyweight Squat
exercises.hint: Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. You can place your hands behind your head. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bodyweight Walking Lunge
exercises.hint: Begin standing with your feet shoulder width apart and your hands on your hips.

exercises.name: Bosu Ball Cable Crunch With Side Bends
exercises.hint: Connect a standard handle to each arm of a cable machine, and position them in the most downward position.

exercises.name: Bottoms Up
exercises.hint: Begin by lying on your back on the ground. Your legs should be straight and your arms at your side. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Bottoms-Up Clean From The Hang Position
exercises.hint: Initiate the exercise by standing upright with a kettlebell in one hand.

exercises.name: Box Jump (Multiple Response)
exercises.hint: Assume a relaxed stance facing the box or platform approximately an arm's length away. Arms should be down at the sides and legs slightly bent.

exercises.name: Box Skip
exercises.hint: You will need several boxes lined up about 8 feet apart.

exercises.name: Box Squat
exercises.hint: The box squat allows you to squat to desired depth and develop explosive strength in the squat movement. Begin in a power rack with a box at the appropriate height behind you. Typically, you would aim for a box height that brings you to a parallel squat, but you can train higher or lower if desired.

exercises.name: Box Squat with Bands
exercises.hint: Begin in a power rack with a box at the appropriate height behind you. Set up the bands on the sleeves, secured to either band pegs, the rack, or dumbbells so that there is appropriate tension. If dumbbells are used, secure them so that they don't move. Also, ensure that the dumbbells you are using are heavy enough for the bands that you are using. Additional plates can be used to hold the dumbbells down. If more tension is needed, you can either widen the base on the floor or choke the bands. Typically, you would aim for a box height that brings you to a parallel squat, but you can train higher or lower if desired.

exercises.name: Box Squat with Chains
exercises.hint: Begin in a power rack with a box at the appropriate height behind you. Typically, you would aim for a box height that brings you to a parallel squat, but you can train higher or lower if desired.

exercises.name: Brachialis-SMR
exercises.hint: Lie on your side, with your upper arm against the foam roller. The upper arm should be more or less aligned with your body, with the outside of the bicep pressed against the foam roller.

exercises.name: Bradford/Rocky Presses
exercises.hint: Sit on a Military Press Bench with a bar at shoulder level with a pronated grip (palms facing forward). Tip: Your grip should be wider than shoulder width and it should create a 90-degree angle between the forearm and the upper arm as the barbell goes down. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Butt Lift (Bridge)
exercises.hint: Lie flat on the floor on your back with the hands by your side and your knees bent. Your feet should be placed around shoulder width. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Butt-Ups
exercises.hint: Begin a pushup position but with your elbows on the ground and resting on your forearms. Your arms should be bent at a 90 degree angle.

exercises.name: Butterfly
exercises.hint: Sit on the machine with your back flat on the pad.

exercises.name: Cable Chest Press
exercises.hint: Adjust the weight to an appropriate amount and be seated, grasping the handles. Your upper arms should be about 45 degrees to the body, with your head and chest up. The elbows should be bent to about 90 degrees. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Cable Crossover
exercises.hint: To get yourself into the starting position, place the pulleys on a high position (above your head), select the resistance to be used and hold the pulleys in each hand.

exercises.name: Cable Crunch
exercises.hint: Kneel below a high pulley that contains a rope attachment.

exercises.name: Cable Deadlifts
exercises.hint: Move the cables to the bottom of the towers and select an appropriate weight. Stand directly in between the uprights.

exercises.name: Cable Hammer Curls - Rope Attachment
exercises.hint: Attach a rope attachment to a low pulley and stand facing the machine about 12 inches away from it.

exercises.name: Cable Hip Adduction
exercises.hint: Stand in front of a low pulley facing forward with one leg next to the pulley and the other one away.

exercises.name: Cable Incline Pushdown
exercises.hint: Lie on incline an bench facing away from a high pulley machine that has a straight bar attachment on it.

exercises.name: Cable Incline Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Lie on incline an bench facing away from a high pulley machine that has a straight bar attachment on it.

exercises.name: Cable Internal Rotation
exercises.hint: Sit next to a low pulley sideways (with legs stretched in front of you or crossed) and grasp the single hand cable attachment with the arm nearest to the cable. Tip: If you can adjust the pulley's height, you can use a flat bench to sit on instead.

exercises.name: Cable Iron Cross
exercises.hint: Begin by moving the pulleys to the high position, select the resistance to be used, and take a handle in each hand.

exercises.name: Cable Judo Flip
exercises.hint: Connect a rope attachment to a tower, and move the cable to the lowest pulley position. Stand with your side to the cable with a wide stance, and grab the rope with both hands.

exercises.name: Cable Lying Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Lie on a flat bench and grasp the straight bar attachment of a low pulley with a narrow overhand grip. Tip: The easiest way to do this is to have someone hand you the bar as you lay down.

exercises.name: Cable One Arm Tricep Extension
exercises.hint: With your right hand, grasp a single handle attached to the high-cable pulley using a supinated (underhand; palms facing up) grip. You should be standing directly in front of the weight stack.

exercises.name: Cable Preacher Curl
exercises.hint: Place a preacher bench about 2 feet in front of a pulley machine.

exercises.name: Cable Rear Delt Fly
exercises.hint: Adjust the pulleys to the appropriate height and adjust the weight. The pulleys should be above your head.

exercises.name: Cable Reverse Crunch
exercises.hint: Connect an ankle strap attachment to a low pulley cable and position a mat on the floor in front of it.

exercises.name: Cable Rope Overhead Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Attach a rope to the bottom pulley of the pulley machine.

exercises.name: Cable Rope Rear-Delt Rows
exercises.hint: Sit in the same position on a low pulley row station as you would if you were doing seated cable rows for the back.

exercises.name: Cable Russian Twists
exercises.hint: Connect a standard handle attachment, and position the cable to a middle pulley position.

exercises.name: Cable Seated Crunch
exercises.hint: Seat on a flat bench with your back facing a high pulley.

exercises.name: Cable Seated Lateral Raise
exercises.hint: Stand in the middle of two low pulleys that are opposite to each other and place a flat bench right behind you (in perpendicular fashion to you; the narrow edge of the bench should be the one behind you). Select the weight to be used on each pulley.

exercises.name: Cable Shoulder Press
exercises.hint: Move the cables to the bottom of the towers and select an appropriate weight.

exercises.name: Cable Shrugs
exercises.hint: Grasp a cable bar attachment that is attached to a low pulley with a shoulder width or slightly wider overhand (palms facing down) grip.

exercises.name: Cable Wrist Curl
exercises.hint: Start out by placing a flat bench in front of a low pulley cable that has a straight bar attachment.

exercises.name: Calf Press
exercises.hint: Adjust the seat so that your legs are only slightly bent in the start position. The balls of your feet should be firmly on the platform.

exercises.name: Calf Press On The Leg Press Machine
exercises.hint: Using a leg press machine, sit down on the machine and place your legs on the platform directly in front of you at a medium (shoulder width) foot stance.

exercises.name: Calf Raise On A Dumbbell
exercises.hint: Hang on to a sturdy object for balance and stand on a dumbbell handle, preferably one with round plates so that it rolls as in this manner you have to work harder to stabilize yourself; thus increasing the effectiveness of the exercise.

exercises.name: Calf Raises - With Bands
exercises.hint: Grab an exercise band and stand on it with your toes making sure that the length of the band between the foot and the arms is the same for both sides.

exercises.name: Calf Stretch Elbows Against Wall
exercises.hint: Stand facing a wall from a couple feet away.

exercises.name: Calf Stretch Hands Against Wall
exercises.hint: Stand facing a wall from several feet away. Stagger your stance, placing one foot forward.

exercises.name: Calves-SMR
exercises.hint: Begin seated on the floor. Place a foam roller underneath your lower leg. Your other leg can either be crossed over the opposite or be placed on the floor, supporting some of your weight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Car Deadlift
exercises.hint: This event apparatus typically has neutral grip handles, however some have a straight bar that you can approach like a normal deadlift. The apparatus can be loaded with a vehicle or other heavy objects such as tractor tires or kegs.

exercises.name: Car Drivers
exercises.hint: While standing upright, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o'clock positions. Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended straight out in front of you. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Carioca Quick Step
exercises.hint: Begin with your feet a few inches apart and your left arm up in a relaxed, athletic position.

exercises.name: Cat Stretch
exercises.hint: Position yourself on the floor on your hands and knees.

exercises.name: Catch and Overhead Throw
exercises.hint: Begin standing while facing a wall or a partner.

exercises.name: Chain Handle Extension
exercises.hint: You will need two cable handle attachments and a flat bench, as well as chains, for this exercise. Clip the middle of the chains to the handles, and position yourself on the flat bench. Your elbows should be pointing straight up.

exercises.name: Chain Press
exercises.hint: Begin by connecting the chains to the cable handle attachments. Position yourself on the flat bench in the same position as for a dumbbell press. Your wrists should be pronated and arms perpendicular to the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Chair Leg Extended Stretch
exercises.hint: Sit upright in a chair and grip the seat on the sides.

exercises.name: Chair Lower Back Stretch
exercises.hint: Sit upright on a chair.

exercises.name: Chair Squat
exercises.hint: To begin, first set the bar to a position that best matches your height. Once the bar is loaded, step under it and position it across the back of your shoulders.

exercises.name: Chair Upper Body Stretch
exercises.hint: Sit on the edge of a chair, gripping the back of it.

exercises.name: Chest And Front Of Shoulder Stretch
exercises.hint: Start off by standing with your legs together, holding a bodybar or a broomstick.

exercises.name: Chest Push from 3 point stance
exercises.hint: Begin in a three point stance, squatted down with your back flat and one hand on the ground. Place the medicine ball directly in front of you.

exercises.name: Chest Push (multiple response)
exercises.hint: Begin in a kneeling position facing a wall or utilize a partner. Hold the ball with both hands tight into the chest.

exercises.name: Chest Push (single response)
exercises.hint: Begin in a kneeling position holding the medicine ball with both hands tightly into the chest.

exercises.name: Chest Push with Run Release
exercises.hint: Begin in an athletic stance with the knees bent, hips back, and back flat. Hold the medicine ball near your legs. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Chest Stretch on Stability Ball
exercises.hint: Get on your hands and knees next to an exercise ball.

exercises.name: Child's Pose
exercises.hint: Get on your hands and knees, walk your hands in front of you.

exercises.name: Chin To Chest Stretch
exercises.hint: Get into a seated position on the floor.

exercises.name: Chin-Up
exercises.hint: Grab the pull-up bar with the palms facing your torso and a grip closer than the shoulder width.

exercises.name: Circus Bell
exercises.hint: The circus bell is an oversized dumbbell with a thick handle. Begin with the dumbbell between your feet, and grip the handle with both hands.

exercises.name: Clean
exercises.hint: With a barbell on the floor close to the shins, take an overhand (or hook) grip just outside the legs. Lower your hips with the weight focused on the heels, back straight, head facing forward, chest up, with your shoulders just in front of the bar. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Clean and Jerk
exercises.hint: With a barbell on the floor close to the shins, take an overhand or hook grip just outside the legs. Lower your hips with the weight focused on the heels, back straight, head facing forward, chest up, with your shoulders just in front of the bar. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Clean and Press
exercises.hint: Assume a shoulder-width stance, with knees inside the arms. Now while keeping the back flat, bend at the knees and hips so that you can grab the bar with the arms fully extended and a pronated grip that is slightly wider than shoulder width. Point the elbows out to sides. The bar should be close to the shins. Position the shoulders over or slightly ahead of the bar. Establish a flat back posture. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Clean Deadlift
exercises.hint: Begin standing with a barbell close to your shins. Your feet should be directly under your hips with your feet turned out slightly. Grip the bar with a double overhand grip or hook grip, about shoulder width apart. Squat down to the bar. Your spine should be in full extension, with a back angle that places your shoulders in front of the bar and your back as vertical as possible.

exercises.name: Clean from Blocks
exercises.hint: With a barbell on boxes or stands of the desired height, take an overhand or hook grip just outside the legs. Lower your hips with the weight focused on the heels, back straight, head facing forward, chest up, with your shoulders just in front of the bar. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Clean Pull
exercises.hint: With a barbell on the floor close to the shins, take an overhand or hook grip just outside the legs. Lower your hips with the weight focused on the heels, back straight, head facing forward, chest up, with your shoulders just in front of the bar. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Clean Shrug
exercises.hint: Begin with a shoulder width, double overhand or hook grip, with the bar hanging at the mid thigh position. Your back should be straight and inclined slightly forward.

exercises.name: Clock Push-Up
exercises.hint: Move into a prone position on the floor, supporting your weight on your hands and toes.

exercises.name: Close-Grip Barbell Bench Press
exercises.hint: Lie back on a flat bench. Using a close grip (around shoulder width), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Close-Grip Dumbbell Press
exercises.hint: Place a dumbbell standing up on a flat bench.

exercises.name: Close-Grip EZ Bar Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright while holding an E-Z Curl Bar at the closer inner handle. The palm of your hands should be facing forward and they should be slightly tilted inwards due to the shape of the bar. The elbows should be close to the torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Close-Grip EZ-Bar Curl with Band
exercises.hint: Attach a band to each end of the bar. Take the bar, placing a foot on the middle of the band. Stand upright with a narrow, supinated grip on the EZ bar. The elbows should be close to the torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Close-Grip EZ-Bar Press
exercises.hint: Lie on a flat bench with an EZ bar loaded to an appropriate weight.

exercises.name: Close-Grip Front Lat Pulldown
exercises.hint: Sit down on a pull-down machine with a wide bar attached to the top pulley. Make sure that you adjust the knee pad of the machine to fit your height. These pads will prevent your body from being raised by the resistance attached to the bar.

exercises.name: Close-Grip Push-Up off of a Dumbbell
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor and place your hands on an upright dumbbell. Supporting your weight on your toes and hands, keep your torso rigid and your elbows in with your arms straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Close-Grip Standing Barbell Curl
exercises.hint: Hold a barbell with both hands, palms up and a few inches apart.

exercises.name: Cocoons
exercises.hint: Begin by lying on your back on the ground. Your legs should be straight and your arms extended behind your head. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Conan's Wheel
exercises.hint: With the weight loaded, take a zurcher hold on the end of the implement. Place the bar in the crook of the elbow and hold onto your wrist. Try to keep the weight off of the forearms.

exercises.name: Concentration Curls
exercises.hint: Sit down on a flat bench with one dumbbell in front of you between your legs. Your legs should be spread with your knees bent and feet on the floor.

exercises.name: Cross-Body Crunch
exercises.hint: Lie flat on your back and bend your knees about 60 degrees.

exercises.name: Cross Body Hammer Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up straight with a dumbbell in each hand. Your hands should be down at your side with your palms facing in.

exercises.name: Cross Over - With Bands
exercises.hint: Secure an exercise band around a stationary post.

exercises.name: Crossover Reverse Lunge
exercises.hint: Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Crucifix
exercises.hint: In the crucifix, you statically hold weights out to the side for time. While the event can be practiced using dumbbells, it is best to practice with one of the various implements used, such as axes and hammers, as it feels different.

exercises.name: Crunch - Hands Overhead
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor with your back flat and knees bent with around a 60-degree angle between the hamstrings and the calves.

exercises.name: Crunch - Legs On Exercise Ball
exercises.hint: Lie flat on your back with your feet resting on an exercise ball and your knees bent at a 90 degree angle.

exercises.name: Crunches
exercises.hint: Lie flat on your back with your feet flat on the ground, or resting on a bench with your knees bent at a 90 degree angle. If you are resting your feet on a bench, place them three to four inches apart and point your toes inward so they touch.

exercises.name: Cuban Press
exercises.hint: Take a dumbbell in each hand with a pronated grip in a standing position. Raise your upper arms so that they are parallel to the floor, allowing your lower arms to hang in the "scarecrow" position. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dancer's Stretch
exercises.hint: Sit up on the floor.

exercises.name: Dead Bug
exercises.hint: Begin lying on your back with your hands extended above you toward the ceiling.

exercises.name: Deadlift with Bands
exercises.hint: To deadlift with short bands, simply loop them over the bar before you start, and step into them to set up. For long bands, they will need to be anchored to a secure base, such as heavy dumbbells or a rack.

exercises.name: Deadlift with Chains
exercises.hint: You can attach the chains to the sleeves of the bar, or just drape the middle over the bar so there is a greater weight increase as you lift.

exercises.name: Decline Barbell Bench Press
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and slowly lay down on the bench.

exercises.name: Decline Close-Grip Bench To Skull Crusher
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and slowly lay down on the bench.

exercises.name: Decline Crunch
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and lie down.

exercises.name: Decline Dumbbell Bench Press
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and lie down with a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Decline Dumbbell Flyes
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and lie down with a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Decline Dumbbell Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and lie down with a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Decline EZ Bar Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and slowly lay down on the bench.

exercises.name: Decline Oblique Crunch
exercises.hint: Secure your legs at the end of the decline bench and slowly lay down on the bench.

exercises.name: Decline Push-Up
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor face down and place your hands about 36 inches apart while holding your torso up at arms length. Move your feet up to a box or bench. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Decline Reverse Crunch
exercises.hint: Lie on your back on a decline bench and hold on to the top of the bench with both hands. Don't let your body slip down from this position.

exercises.name: Decline Smith Press
exercises.hint: Place a decline bench underneath the Smith machine. Now place the barbell at a height that you can reach when lying down and your arms are almost fully extended. Using a pronated grip that is wider than shoulder width, unlock the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms extended. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Deficit Deadlift
exercises.hint: Begin by having a platform or weight plates that you can stand on, usually 1-3 inches in height. Approach the bar so that it is centered over your feet. You feet should be about hip width apart. Bend at the hip to grip the bar at shoulder width, allowing your shoulder blades to protract. Typically, you would use an overhand grip or an over/under grip on heavier sets.

exercises.name: Depth Jump Leap
exercises.hint: For this drill you will need two boxes or benches, one 12 to 16 inches high and the other 22 to 26 inches high.

exercises.name: Dip Machine
exercises.hint: Sit securely in a dip machine, select the weight and firmly grasp the handles.

exercises.name: Dips - Triceps Version
exercises.hint: To get into the starting position, hold your body at arm's length with your arms nearly locked above the bars.

exercises.name: Donkey Calf Raises
exercises.hint: For this exercise you will need access to a donkey calf raise machine. Start by positioning your lower back and hips under the padded lever provided. The tailbone area should be the one making contact with the pad.

exercises.name: Double Kettlebell Alternating Hang Clean
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells between your feet. To get in the starting position, push your butt back and look straight ahead.

exercises.name: Double Kettlebell Jerk
exercises.hint: Hold a kettlebell by the handle in each hand.

exercises.name: Double Kettlebell Push Press
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders.

exercises.name: Double Kettlebell Snatch
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells behind your feet. Bend your knees and sit back to pick up the kettlebells.

exercises.name: Double Kettlebell Windmill
exercises.hint: Place a kettlebell in front of your front foot and clean and press a kettlebell overhead with your opposite arm. Clean the kettlebell to your shoulder by extending through the legs and hips as you pull the kettlebell towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrist as you do so, so that the palm faces forward.

exercises.name: Double Leg Butt Kick
exercises.hint: Begin standing with your knees slightly bent.

exercises.name: Downward Facing Balance
exercises.hint: Lie facedown on top of an exercise ball.

exercises.name: Drag Curl
exercises.hint: Grab a barbell with a supinated grip (palms facing forward) and get your elbows close to your torso and back. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Drop Push
exercises.hint: Position low boxes or other platforms 2-3 feet apart.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Alternate Bicep Curl
exercises.hint: Stand (torso upright) with a dumbbell in each hand held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso and the palms of your hand should be facing your thighs.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Bench Press
exercises.hint: Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell in each hand resting on top of your thighs. The palms of your hands will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Bench Press with Neutral Grip
exercises.hint: Take a dumbbell in each hand and lay back onto a flat bench. Your feet should be flat on the floor and your shoulder blades retracted.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Bicep Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up straight with a dumbbell in each hand at arm's length. Keep your elbows close to your torso and rotate the palms of your hands until they are facing forward. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Clean
exercises.hint: Begin standing with a dumbbell in each hand with your feet shoulder width apart.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Floor Press
exercises.hint: Lay on the floor holding dumbbells in your hands. Your knees can be bent. Begin with the weights fully extended above you.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Flyes
exercises.hint: Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell on each hand resting on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Incline Row
exercises.hint: Using a neutral grip, lean into an incline bench.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Incline Shoulder Raise
exercises.hint: Sit on an Incline Bench while holding a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Lunges
exercises.hint: Stand with your torso upright holding two dumbbells in your hands by your sides. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Lying One-Arm Rear Lateral Raise
exercises.hint: While holding a dumbbell in one hand, lay with your chest down on a slightly inclined (around 15 degrees when measured from the floor) adjustable bench. The other hand can be used to hold to the leg of the bench for stability.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Lying Rear Lateral Raise
exercises.hint: While holding a dumbbell in each hand, lay with your chest down on a slightly inclined (around 15 degrees when measured from the floor) adjustable bench.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Lying Supination
exercises.hint: Lie sideways on a flat bench with one arm holding a dumbbell and the other hand on top of the bench folded so that you can rest your head on it.

exercises.name: Dumbbell One-Arm Shoulder Press
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell and either sit on a military press bench or a utility bench that has a back support on it as you place the dumbbells upright on top of your thighs or stand up straight.

exercises.name: Dumbbell One-Arm Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell and either sit on a military press bench or a utility bench that has a back support on it as you place the dumbbells upright on top of your thighs or stand up straight.

exercises.name: Dumbbell One-Arm Upright Row
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell and stand up straight with your arm extended in front of you with a slight bend at the elbows and your back straight. This will be your starting position. Tip: The dumbbell should be resting on top of your thigh with the palm of your hands facing your thighs.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Prone Incline Curl
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell on each hand and lie face down on an incline bench with your shoulders near top of the incline. Your knees can rest on the seat or your legs can be straddled to the sides (my preferred way).

exercises.name: Dumbbell Raise
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell in each arm and stand up straight with your arms extended by your sides with a slight bend at the elbows and your back straight. This will be your starting position. Tip: The dumbbell should be next to your thighs with the palm of your hands facing back.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Rear Lunge
exercises.hint: Stand with your torso upright holding two dumbbells in your hands by your sides. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Scaption
exercises.hint: This corrective exercise strengthens the muscles that stabilize your shoulder blade. Hold a light weight in each hand, hanging at your sides. Your thumbs should pointing up.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Seated Box Jump
exercises.hint: Position a box a couple feet to the side of a bench. Hold a dumbbell to your chest with both hands and seat yourself on the bench facing the box. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Seated One-Leg Calf Raise
exercises.hint: Place a block on the floor about 12 inches from a flat bench.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Shoulder Press
exercises.hint: While holding a dumbbell in each hand, sit on a military press bench or utility bench that has back support. Place the dumbbells upright on top of your thighs.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Shrug
exercises.hint: Stand erect with a dumbbell on each hand (palms facing your torso), arms extended on the sides.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Side Bend
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell on the left hand (palms facing the torso) as you have the right hand holding your waist. Your feet should be placed at shoulder width. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dumbbell Squat
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell on each hand (palms facing the side of your legs).

exercises.name: Dumbbell Squat To A Bench
exercises.hint: Stand up straight with a flat bench behind you while holding a dumbbell on each hand (palms facing the side of your legs).

exercises.name: Dumbbell Step Ups
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding a dumbbell on each hand (palms facing the side of your legs).

exercises.name: Dumbbell Tricep Extension -Pronated Grip
exercises.hint: Lie down on a flat bench holding two dumbbells directly above your shoulders. Your arms should be fully extended and form a 90 degree angle from your torso and the floor.

exercises.name: Dynamic Back Stretch
exercises.hint: Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Dynamic Chest Stretch
exercises.hint: Stand with your hands together, arms extended directly in front of you. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Elbow Circles
exercises.hint: Sit or stand with your feet slightly apart.

exercises.name: Elbow to Knee
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor, crossing your right leg across your bent left knee. Clasp your hands behind your head, beginning with your shoulder blades on the ground. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Elbows Back
exercises.hint: Stand up straight.

exercises.name: Elevated Back Lunge
exercises.hint: Position a bar onto a rack at shoulder height loaded to an appropriate weight. Place a short, raised platform behind you.

exercises.name: Elevated Cable Rows
exercises.hint: Get a platform of some sort (it can be an aerobics or calf raise platform) that is around 4-6 inches in height.

exercises.name: Elliptical Trainer
exercises.hint: To begin, step onto the elliptical and select the desired option from the menu. Most ellipticals have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout.

exercises.name: Exercise Ball Crunch
exercises.hint: Lie on an exercise ball with your lower back curvature pressed against the spherical surface of the ball. Your feet should be bent at the knee and pressed firmly against the floor. The upper torso should be hanging off the top of the ball. The arms should either be kept alongside the body or crossed on top of your chest as these positions avoid neck strains (as opposed to the hands behind the back of the head position).

exercises.name: Exercise Ball Pull-In
exercises.hint: Place an exercise ball nearby and lay on the floor in front of it with your hands on the floor shoulder width apart in a push-up position.

exercises.name: Extended Range One-Arm Kettlebell Floor Press
exercises.hint: Lie on the floor and position a kettlebell for one arm to press. The kettlebell should be held by the handle. The leg on the same side that you are pressing should be bent, with the knee crossing over the midline of the body.

exercises.name: External Rotation
exercises.hint: Lie sideways on a flat bench with one arm holding a dumbbell and the other hand on top of the bench folded so that you can rest your head on it.

exercises.name: External Rotation with Band
exercises.hint: Choke the band around a post. The band should be at the same height as your elbow. Stand with your left side to the band a couple of feet away.

exercises.name: External Rotation with Cable
exercises.hint: Adjust the cable to the same height as your elbow. Stand with your left side to the band a couple of feet away.

exercises.name: EZ-Bar Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up straight while holding an EZ curl bar at the wide outer handle. The palms of your hands should be facing forward and slightly tilted inward due to the shape of the bar. Keep your elbows close to your torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: EZ-Bar Skullcrusher
exercises.hint: Using a close grip, lift the EZ bar and hold it with your elbows in as you lie on the bench. Your arms should be perpendicular to the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Face Pull
exercises.hint: Facing a high pulley with a rope or dual handles attached, pull the weight directly towards your face, separating your hands as you do so. Keep your upper arms parallel to the ground.

exercises.name: Fast Skipping
exercises.hint: Start in a relaxed position with one leg slightly forward. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Finger Curls
exercises.hint: Hold a barbell with both hands and your palms facing up; hands spaced about shoulder width.

exercises.name: Flat Bench Leg Pull-In
exercises.hint: Lie on an exercise mat or a flat bench with your legs off the end.

exercises.name: Flat Bench Lying Leg Raise
exercises.hint: Lie with your back flat on a bench and your legs extended in front of you off the end.

exercises.name: Flexor Incline Dumbbell Curls
exercises.hint: Hold the dumbbell towards the side farther from you so that you have more weight on the side closest to you. (This can be done for a good effect on all bicep dumbbell exercises). Now do a normal incline dumbbell curl, but keep your wrists as far back as possible so as to neutralize any stress that is placed on them.

exercises.name: Floor Glute-Ham Raise
exercises.hint: You can use a partner for this exercise or brace your feet under something stable.

exercises.name: Floor Press
exercises.hint: Adjust the j-hooks so they are at the appropriate height to rack the bar. Begin lying on the floor with your head near the end of a power rack. Keeping your shoulder blades pulled together; pull the bar off of the hooks.

exercises.name: Floor Press with Chains
exercises.hint: Adjust the j-hooks so they are at the appropriate height to rack the bar. For this exercise, drape the chains directly over the end of the bar, trying to keep the ends away from the plates.

exercises.name: Flutter Kicks
exercises.hint: On a flat bench lie facedown with the hips on the edge of the bench, the legs straight with toes high off the floor and with the arms on top of the bench holding on to the front edge.

exercises.name: Foot-SMR
exercises.hint: This exercise stretches the fascia of the muscles in the feet. Start off seated with your shoes removed. Using a foot roller or a similar object, such as a small section of pvc pipe, place your foot against the roller across the arch of your foot. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Forward Drag with Press
exercises.hint: Attach a dual handled chain or rope attachment to the sled. You should be facing away from the sled, holding a handle in each hand.

exercises.name: Frankenstein Squat
exercises.hint: This drill teaches you the proper positioning of both the bar and your body during the clean and front squat.

exercises.name: Frog Hops
exercises.hint: Stand with your hands behind your head, and squat down keeping your torso upright and your head up. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Frog Sit-Ups
exercises.hint: Lie with your back flat on the floor (or exercise mat) and your legs extended in front of you.

exercises.name: Front Barbell Squat
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, bring your arms up under the bar while keeping the elbows high and the upper arm slightly above parallel to the floor. Rest the bar on top of the deltoids and cross your arms while grasping the bar for total control.

exercises.name: Front Barbell Squat To A Bench
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set a flat bench behind you and set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, bring your arms up under the bar while keeping the elbows high and the upper arm slightly above parallel to the floor. Rest the bar on top of the deltoids and cross your arms while grasping the bar for total control.

exercises.name: Front Box Jump
exercises.hint: Begin with a box of an appropriate height 1-2 feet in front of you. Stand with your feet should width apart. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Front Cable Raise
exercises.hint: Select the weight on a low pulley machine and grasp the single hand cable attachment that is attached to the low pulley with your left hand.

exercises.name: Front Dumbbell Raise
exercises.hint: Pick a couple of dumbbells and stand with a straight torso and the dumbbells on front of your thighs at arms length with the palms of the hand facing your thighs. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Front Incline Dumbbell Raise
exercises.hint: Sit down on an incline bench with the incline set anywhere between 30 to 60 degrees while holding a dumbbell on each hand. Tip: You can change the angle to hit the muscle a little differently each time.

exercises.name: Front Leg Raises
exercises.hint: Stand next to a chair or other support, holding on with one hand.

exercises.name: Front Plate Raise
exercises.hint: While standing straight, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o'clock positions. Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended and locked with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate should be down near your waist in front of you as far as you can go. Tip: The arms will remain in this position throughout the exercise. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Front Raise And Pullover
exercises.hint: Lie on a flat bench while holding a barbell using a palms down grip that is about 15 inches apart.

exercises.name: Front Squat (Clean Grip)
exercises.hint: To begin, first set the bar in a rack slightly below shoulder level. Rest the bar on top of the deltoids, pushing into the clavicles, and lightly touching the throat. Your hands should be in a clean grip, touching the bar only with your fingers to help keep it in position.

exercises.name: Front Squats With Two Kettlebells
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders. Clean the kettlebells to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you pull the kettlebells towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrists as you do so.

exercises.name: Front Two-Dumbbell Raise
exercises.hint: Pick a couple of dumbbells and stand with a straight torso and the dumbbells on front of your thighs at arms length with the palms of the hand facing your thighs. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Full Range-Of-Motion Lat Pulldown
exercises.hint: Either standing or seated on a high bench, grasp two stirrup cables that are attached to the high pulleys. Grab with the opposing hand so your arms are crisscrossed about you and your palms are facing forward.

exercises.name: Gironda Sternum Chins
exercises.hint: Grasp the pull-up bar with a shoulder width underhand grip.

exercises.name: Glute Ham Raise
exercises.hint: Begin by adjusting the equipment to fit your body. Place your feet against the footplate in between the rollers as you lie facedown. Your knees should be just behind the pad.

exercises.name: Glute Kickback
exercises.hint: Kneel on the floor or an exercise mat and bend at the waist with your arms extended in front of you (perpendicular to the torso) in order to get into a kneeling push-up position but with the arms spaced at shoulder width. Your head should be looking forward and the bend of the knees should create a 90-degree angle between the hamstrings and the calves. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Goblet Squat
exercises.hint: Stand holding a light kettlebell by the horns close to your chest. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Good Morning
exercises.hint: Begin with a bar on a rack at shoulder height. Rack the bar across the rear of your shoulders as you would a power squat, not on top of your shoulders. Keep your back tight, shoulder blades pinched together, and your knees slightly bent. Step back from the rack.

exercises.name: Good Morning off Pins
exercises.hint: Begin with a bar on a rack at about the same height as your stomach. Bend over underneath the bar and rack the bar across the rear of your shoulders as you would a power squat, not on top of your shoulders. At the proper height, you should be near parallel to the floor when bent over. Keep your back tight, shoulder blades pinched together, and your knees slightly bent. Keep your back arched and your cervical spine in proper alignment.

exercises.name: Gorilla Chin/Crunch
exercises.hint: Hang from a chin-up bar using an underhand grip (palms facing you) that is slightly wider than shoulder width.

exercises.name: Groin and Back Stretch
exercises.hint: Sit on the floor with your knees bent and feet together.

exercises.name: Groiners
exercises.hint: Begin in a pushup position on the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Hack Squat
exercises.hint: Place the back of your torso against the back pad of the machine and hook your shoulders under the shoulder pads provided.

exercises.name: Hammer Curls
exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright and a dumbbell on each hand being held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso.

exercises.name: Hammer Grip Incline DB Bench Press
exercises.hint: Lie back on an incline bench with a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Hamstring-SMR
exercises.hint: In a seated position, extend your legs over a foam roll so that it is position on the back of the upper legs. Place your hands to the side or behind you to help support your weight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Hamstring Stretch
exercises.hint: Lie on your back with one leg extended above you, with the hip at ninety degrees. Keep the other leg flat on the floor.

exercises.name: Handstand Push-Ups
exercises.hint: With your back to the wall bend at the waist and place both hands on the floor at shoulder width.

exercises.name: Hang Clean
exercises.hint: Begin with a shoulder width, double overhand or hook grip, with the bar hanging at the mid thigh position. Your back should be straight and inclined slightly forward.

exercises.name: Hang Clean - Below the Knees
exercises.hint: Begin with a shoulder width, double overhand or hook grip, with the bar hanging just below the knees. Your back should be straight and inclined slightly forward.

exercises.name: Hang Snatch
exercises.hint: Begin with a wide grip on the bar, with an overhand or hook grip. The feet should be directly below the hips with the feet turned out. Your knees should be slightly bent, and the torso inclined forward. The spine should be fully extended and the head facing forward. The bar should be at the hips. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Hang Snatch - Below Knees
exercises.hint: Begin with a wide grip on the bar, with an overhand or hook grip. The feet should be directly below the hips with the feet turned out. Your knees should be slightly bent, and the torso inclined forward. The spine should be fully extended and the head facing forward. The bar should be just below the knees. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Hanging Pike
exercises.hint: Hang from a chin-up bar with your legs and feet together using an overhand grip (palms facing away from you) that is slightly wider than shoulder width. Tip: You may use wrist wraps in order to facilitate holding on to the bar.

exercises.name: Heaving Snatch Balance
exercises.hint: This drill helps you learn the snatch. Begin by holding a light weight across the back of the shoulders. Your feet should be slightly wider than hip width apart with the feet turned out, the same position that you would perform a squat with.

exercises.name: Heavy Bag Thrust
exercises.hint: Utilize a heavy bag for this exercise. Assume an upright stance next to the bag, with your feet staggered, fairly wide apart. Place your hand on the bag at about chest height. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: High Cable Curls
exercises.hint: Stand between a couple of high pulleys and grab a handle in each arm. Position your upper arms in a way that they are parallel to the floor with the palms of your hands facing you. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Hip Circles (prone)
exercises.hint: Position yourself on your hands and knees on the ground. Maintaining good posture, raise one bent knee off of the ground. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Hip Extension with Bands
exercises.hint: Secure one end of the band to the lower portion of a post and attach the other to one ankle.

exercises.name: Hip Flexion with Band
exercises.hint: Secure one end of the band to the lower portion of a post and attach the other to one ankle.

exercises.name: Hip Lift with Band
exercises.hint: After choosing a suitable band, lay down in the middle of the rack, after securing the band on either side of you. If your rack doesn't have pegs, the band can be secured using heavy dumbbells or similar objects, just ensure they won't move.

exercises.name: Hug A Ball
exercises.hint: Seat yourself on the floor.

exercises.name: Hug Knees To Chest
exercises.hint: Lie down on your back and pull both knees up to your chest.

exercises.name: Hurdle Hops
exercises.hint: Set up a row of hurdles or other small barriers, placing them a few feet apart.

exercises.name: Hyperextensions (Back Extensions)
exercises.hint: Lie face down on a hyperextension bench, tucking your ankles securely under the footpads.

exercises.name: Hyperextensions With No Hyperextension Bench
exercises.hint: With someone holding down your legs, slide yourself down to the edge a flat bench until your hips hang off the end of the bench. Tip: Your entire upper body should be hanging down towards the floor. Also, you will be in the same position as if you were on a hyperextension bench but the range of motion will be shorter due to the height of the flat bench vs. that of the hyperextension bench.

exercises.name: Iliotibial Tract-SMR
exercises.hint: Lay on your side, with the bottom leg placed onto a foam roller between the hip and the knee. The other leg can be crossed in front of you.

exercises.name: Inchworm
exercises.hint: Stand with your feet close together. Keeping your legs straight, stretch down and put your hands on the floor directly in front of you. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Incline Barbell Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Hold a barbell with an overhand grip (palms down) that is a little closer together than shoulder width.

exercises.name: Incline Bench Pull
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and lie face down on an incline bench that is set to an incline that is approximately 30 degrees.

exercises.name: Incline Cable Chest Press
exercises.hint: Adjust the weight to an appropriate amount and be seated, grasping the handles. Your upper arms should be about 45 degrees to the body, with your head and chest up. The elbows should be bent to about 90 degrees. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Incline Cable Flye
exercises.hint: To get yourself into the starting position, set the pulleys at the floor level (lowest level possible on the machine that is below your torso).

exercises.name: Incline Dumbbell Bench With Palms Facing In
exercises.hint: Lie back on an incline bench with a dumbbell on each hand on top of your thighs. The palms of your hand will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Incline Dumbbell Curl
exercises.hint: Sit back on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand held at arms length. Keep your elbows close to your torso and rotate the palms of your hands until they are facing forward. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Incline Dumbbell Flyes
exercises.hint: Hold a dumbbell on each hand and lie on an incline bench that is set to an incline angle of no more than 30 degrees.

exercises.name: Incline Dumbbell Flyes - With A Twist
exercises.hint: Hold a dumbbell in each hand and lie on an incline bench that is set to an incline angle of no more than 30 degrees.

exercises.name: Incline Dumbbell Press
exercises.hint: Lie back on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand atop your thighs. The palms of your hands will be facing each other.

exercises.name: Incline Hammer Curls
exercises.hint: Seat yourself on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand. You should pressed firmly against he back with your feet together. Allow the dumbbells to hang straight down at your side, holding them with a neutral grip. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Incline Inner Biceps Curl
exercises.hint: Hold a dumbbell in each hand and lie back on an incline bench.

exercises.name: Incline Push-Up
exercises.hint: Stand facing bench or sturdy elevated platform. Place hands on edge of bench or platform, slightly wider than shoulder width.

exercises.name: Incline Push-Up Close-Grip
exercises.hint: Stand facing a Smith machine bar or sturdy elevated platform at an appropriate height.

exercises.name: Incline Push-Up Depth Jump
exercises.hint: For this drill you will need a box about 12 inches high, and two thick mats or aerobics steps.

exercises.name: Incline Push-Up Medium
exercises.hint: Stand facing a Smith machine bar or sturdy elevated platform at an appropriate height.

exercises.name: Incline Push-Up Reverse Grip
exercises.hint: Stand facing a Smith machine bar or sturdy elevated platform at an appropriate height.

exercises.name: Incline Push-Up Wide
exercises.hint: Stand facing a Smith machine bar or sturdy elevated platform at an appropriate height.

exercises.name: Intermediate Groin Stretch
exercises.hint: Lie on your back with your legs extended. Loop a belt, rope, or band around one of your feet, and swing that leg as far to the side as you can. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Intermediate Hip Flexor and Quad Stretch
exercises.hint: Lie face down on the floor, with a rope, belt, or band looped around one foot.

exercises.name: Internal Rotation with Band
exercises.hint: Choke the band around a post. The band should be at the same height as your elbow. Stand with your right side to the band a couple of feet away.

exercises.name: Inverted Row
exercises.hint: Position a bar in a rack to about waist height. You can also use a smith machine.

exercises.name: Inverted Row with Straps
exercises.hint: Hang a rope or suspension straps from a rack or other stable object. Grasp the ends and position yourself in a supine position hanging from the ropes. Your body should be straight with your heels on the ground with your arms fully extended. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Iron Crosses (stretch)
exercises.hint: Lie face down on the floor, with your arms extended out to your side, palms pressed to the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Isometric Chest Squeezes
exercises.hint: While either seating or standing, bend your arms at a 90-degree angle and place the palms of your hands together in front of your chest. Tip: Your hands should be open with the palms together and fingers facing forward (perpendicular to your torso).

exercises.name: Isometric Neck Exercise - Front And Back
exercises.hint: With your head and neck in a neutral position (normal position with head erect facing forward), place both of your hands on the front side of your head.

exercises.name: Isometric Neck Exercise - Sides
exercises.hint: With your head and neck in a neutral position (normal position with head erect facing forward), place your left hand on the left side of your head.

exercises.name: Isometric Wipers
exercises.hint: Assume a push-up position, supporting your weight on your hands and toes while keeping your body straight. Your hands should be just outside of shoulder width. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: IT Band and Glute Stretch
exercises.hint: Loop a belt, rope, or band around one of your feet, and swing that leg across your body to the opposite side, keeping the leg extended as you lay on the ground. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Jackknife Sit-Up
exercises.hint: Lie flat on the floor (or exercise mat) on your back with your arms extended straight back behind your head and your legs extended also. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Janda Sit-Up
exercises.hint: Position your body on the floor in the basic sit-up position; knees to a ninety degree angle with feet flat on the floor and arms either crossed over your chest or to the sides. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Jefferson Squats
exercises.hint: Place a barbell on the floor.

exercises.name: Jerk Balance
exercises.hint: This drill helps you learn to drive yourself low enough during the jerk and corrects those who move backward during the movement. Begin with the bar racked in the jerk position, with the shoulders forward, torso upright, and the feet split slightly apart.

exercises.name: Jerk Dip Squat
exercises.hint: This movement strengthens the dip portion of the jerk. Begin with the bar racked in the jerk position, with the shoulders forward to create a shelf and the bar lightly contacting the throat. The feet should be directly under the hips, with the feet turned out as is comfortable.

exercises.name: JM Press
exercises.hint: Start the exercise the same way you would a close grip bench press. You will lie on a flat bench while holding a barbell at arms length (fully extended) with the elbows in. However, instead of having the arms perpendicular to the torso, make sure the bar is set in a direct line above the upper chest. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Jogging, Treadmill
exercises.hint: To begin, step onto the treadmill and select the desired option from the menu. Most treadmills have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout.

exercises.name: Keg Load
exercises.hint: To load kegs, place the desired number a distance from the loading platform, typically 30-50 feet.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Arnold Press
exercises.hint: Clean a kettlebell to your shoulder. Clean the kettlebell to your shoulder by extending through the legs and hips as you raise the kettlebell towards your shoulder. The palm should be facing inward.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Dead Clean
exercises.hint: Place kettlebell between your feet. To get in the starting position, push your butt back and look straight ahead.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Figure 8
exercises.hint: Place one kettlebell between your legs and take a wider than shoulder width stance. Bend over by pushing your butt out and keeping your back flat.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Hang Clean
exercises.hint: Place kettlebell between your feet. To get in the starting position, push your butt back and look straight ahead.

exercises.name: Kettlebell One-Legged Deadlift
exercises.hint: Hold a kettlebell by the handle in one hand. Stand on one leg, on the same side that you hold the kettlebell.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Pass Between The Legs
exercises.hint: Place one kettlebell between your legs and take a comfortable stance. Bend over by pushing your butt out and keeping your back flat.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Pirate Ships
exercises.hint: With a wide stance, hold a kettlebell with both hands. Allow it to hang at waist level with your arms extended. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Pistol Squat
exercises.hint: Pick up a kettlebell with two hands and hold it by the horns. Hold one leg off of the floor and squat down on the other.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Seated Press
exercises.hint: Sit on the floor and spread your legs out comfortably.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Seesaw Press
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells two your shoulders.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Sumo High Pull
exercises.hint: Place a kettlebell on the ground between your feet. Position your feet in a wide stance, and grasp the kettlebell with two hands. Set your hips back as far as possible, with your knees bent. Keep your chest and head up. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Thruster
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders. Clean the kettlebells to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you pull the kettlebells towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrists as you do so. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Turkish Get-Up (Lunge style)
exercises.hint: Lie on your back on the floor and press a kettlebell to the top position by extending the elbow. Bend the knee on the same side as the kettlebell.

exercises.name: Kettlebell Windmill
exercises.hint: Place a kettlebell in front of your lead foot and clean and press it overhead with your opposite arm.
