exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright while holding a cable curl bar that is attached to a low pulley. Grab the cable bar at shoulder width and keep the elbows close to the torso. The palm of your hands should be facing up (supinated grip). This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Biceps Stretch
exercises.hint: Clasp your hands behind your back with your palms together, straighten arms and then rotate them so your palms face downward.

exercises.name: Standing Bradford Press
exercises.hint: Place a loaded bar at shoulder level in a rack. With a pronated grip at shoulder width, begin with the bar racked across the front of your shoulders. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Cable Chest Press
exercises.hint: Position dual pulleys to chest height and select an appropriate weight. Stand a foot or two in front of the cables, holding one in each hand. You can stagger your stance for better stability.

exercises.name: Standing Cable Lift
exercises.hint: Connect a standard handle on a tower, and move the cable to the lowest pulley position.

exercises.name: Standing Cable Wood Chop
exercises.hint: Connect a standard handle to a tower, and move the cable to the highest pulley position.

exercises.name: Standing Calf Raises
exercises.hint: Adjust the padded lever of the calf raise machine to fit your height.

exercises.name: Standing Dumbbell Calf Raise
exercises.hint: Stand with your torso upright holding two dumbbells in your hands by your sides. Place the ball of the foot on a sturdy and stable wooden board (that is around 2-3 inches tall) while your heels extend off and touch the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Dumbbell Press
exercises.hint: Standing with your feet shoulder width apart, take a dumbbell in each hand. Raise the dumbbells to head height, the elbows out and about 90 degrees. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Dumbbell Reverse Curl
exercises.hint: To begin, stand straight with a dumbbell in each hand using a pronated grip (palms facing down). Your arms should be fully extended while your feet are shoulder width apart from each other. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Dumbbell Straight-Arm Front Delt Raise Above Head
exercises.hint: Hold the dumbbells in front of your thighs, palms facing your thighs.

exercises.name: Standing Dumbbell Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: To begin, stand up with a dumbbell held by both hands. Your feet should be about shoulder width apart from each other. Slowly use both hands to grab the dumbbell and lift it over your head until both arms are fully extended.

exercises.name: Standing Dumbbell Upright Row
exercises.hint: Grasp a dumbbell in each hand with a pronated (palms forward) grip that is slightly less than shoulder width. The dumbbells should be resting on top of your thighs. Your arms should be extended with a slight bend at the elbows and your back should be straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Elevated Quad Stretch
exercises.hint: Start by standing with your back about two to three feet away from a bench or step.

exercises.name: Standing Front Barbell Raise Over Head
exercises.hint: To begin, stand straight with a barbell in your hands. You should grip the bar with palms facing down and a closer than shoulder width grip apart from each other.

exercises.name: Standing Gastrocnemius Calf Stretch
exercises.hint: Place your right heel on a step with your knee extended and lean forward to grab your right toe with your right hand. Your left knee should be slightly bent and your back should be straight.

exercises.name: Standing Hamstring and Calf Stretch
exercises.hint: Being by looping a belt, band, or rope around one foot. While standing, place that foot forward.

exercises.name: Standing Hip Circles
exercises.hint: Begin standing on one leg, holding to a vertical support.

exercises.name: Standing Hip Flexors
exercises.hint: Stand up straight with the spine vertical, the left foot slightly in front of the right.

exercises.name: Standing Inner-Biceps Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up with a dumbbell in each hand being held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso. Your legs should be at about shoulder's width apart from each other.

exercises.name: Standing Lateral Stretch
exercises.hint: Take a slightly wider than hip distance stance with your knees slightly bent.

exercises.name: Standing Leg Curl
exercises.hint: Adjust the machine lever to fit your height and lie with your torso bent at the waist facing forward around 30-45 degrees (since an angled position is more favorable for hamstrings recruitment) with the pad of the lever on the back of your right leg (just a few inches under the calves) and the front of the right leg on top of the machine pad.

exercises.name: Standing Long Jump
exercises.hint: This drill is best done in sand or other soft landing surface. Ensure that you are able to measure distance. Stand in a partial squat stance with feet shoulder width apart.

exercises.name: Standing Low-Pulley Deltoid Raise
exercises.hint: Start by standing to the right side of a low pulley row. Use your left hand to come across the body and grab a single handle attached to the low pulley with a pronated grip (palms facing down). Rest your arm in front of you. Your right hand should grab the machine for better support and balance.

exercises.name: Standing Low-Pulley One-Arm Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: Grab a single handle with your left arm next to the low pulley machine. Turn away from the machine keeping the handle to the side of your body with your arm fully extended. Now use both hands to elevate the single handle directly above the head with the palm facing forward. Keep your upper arm completely vertical (perpendicular to the floor) and put your right hand on your left elbow to help keep it steady. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Military Press
exercises.hint: Start by placing a barbell that is about chest high on a squat rack. Once you have selected the weights, grab the barbell using a pronated (palms facing forward) grip. Make sure to grip the bar wider than shoulder width apart from each other.

exercises.name: Standing Olympic Plate Hand Squeeze
exercises.hint: To begin, stand straight while holding a weight plate by the ridge at arm's length in each hand using a neutral grip (palms facing in). You feet should be shoulder width apart from each other. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Standing One-Arm Cable Curl
exercises.hint: Start out by grabbing single handle next to the low pulley machine. Make sure you are far enough from the machine so that your arm is supporting the weight.

exercises.name: Standing One-Arm Dumbbell Curl Over Incline Bench
exercises.hint: Stand on the back side of an incline bench as if you were going to be a spotter for someone. Have a dumbbell in one hand and rest it across the incline bench with a supinated (palms up) grip.

exercises.name: Standing One-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: To begin, stand up with a dumbbell held in one hand. Your feet should be about shoulder width apart from each other. Now fully extend the arm with the dumbbell over your head. Tip: The small finger of your hand should be facing the ceiling and the palm of your hand should be facing forward. The dumbbell should be above your head.

exercises.name: Standing Overhead Barbell Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: To begin, stand up holding a barbell or e-z bar using a pronated grip (palms facing forward) with your hands closer than shoulder width apart from each other. Your feet should be about shoulder width apart.

exercises.name: Standing Palm-In One-Arm Dumbbell Press
exercises.hint: Start by having a dumbbell in one hand with your arm fully extended to the side using a neutral grip. Use your other arm to hold on to an incline bench to keep your balance.

exercises.name: Standing Palms-In Dumbbell Press
exercises.hint: Start by having a dumbbell in each hand with your arm fully extended to the side using a neutral grip. Your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other. Now slowly lift the dumbbells up until you create a 90 degree angle with your arms. Note: Your forearms should be perpendicular to the floor. This the starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Palms-Up Barbell Behind The Back Wrist Curl
exercises.hint: Start by standing straight and holding a barbell behind your glutes at arm's length while using a pronated grip (palms will be facing back away from the glutes) and having your hands shoulder width apart from each other.

exercises.name: Standing Pelvic Tilt
exercises.hint: Start off with your feet hip-distance apart.

exercises.name: Standing Rope Crunch
exercises.hint: Attach a rope to a high pulley and select an appropriate weight.

exercises.name: Standing Soleus And Achilles Stretch
exercises.hint: Stand with your feet hip-distance apart, one foot slightly in front of the other.

exercises.name: Standing Toe Touches
exercises.hint: Stand with some space in front and behind you.

exercises.name: Standing Towel Triceps Extension
exercises.hint: To begin, stand up with both arms fully extended above the head holding one end of a towel with both hands. Your elbows should be in and the arms perpendicular to the floor with the palms facing each other while your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Standing Two-Arm Overhead Throw
exercises.hint: Stand with your feet shoulder width apart holding a medicine ball in both hands. To begin, reach the medicine ball deep behind your head as you bend the knees slightly and lean back.

exercises.name: Star Jump
exercises.hint: Begin in a relaxed stance with your feet shoulder width apart and hold your arms close to the body.

exercises.name: Step Mill
exercises.hint: To begin, step onto the stepmill and select the desired option from the menu. You can choose a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Use caution so that you don't trip as you climb the stairs. It is recommended that you maintain your grip on the handles so that you don't fall.

exercises.name: Step-up with Knee Raise
exercises.hint: Stand facing a box or bench of an appropriate height with your feet together. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Stiff Leg Barbell Good Morning
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.

exercises.name: Stiff-Legged Barbell Deadlift
exercises.hint: Grasp a bar using an overhand grip (palms facing down). You may need some wrist wraps if using a significant amount of weight.

exercises.name: Stiff-Legged Dumbbell Deadlift
exercises.hint: Grasp a couple of dumbbells holding them by your side at arm's length.

exercises.name: Stomach Vacuum
exercises.hint: To begin, stand straight with your feet shoulder width apart from each other. Place your hands on your hips. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Straight-Arm Dumbbell Pullover
exercises.hint: Place a dumbbell standing up on a flat bench.

exercises.name: Straight-Arm Pulldown
exercises.hint: You will start by grabbing the wide bar from the top pulley of a pulldown machine and using a wider than shoulder-width pronated (palms down) grip. Step backwards two feet or so.

exercises.name: Straight Bar Bench Mid Rows
exercises.hint: Place a loaded barbell on the end of a bench. Standing on the bench behind the bar, take a medium, pronated grip. Stand with your hips back and chest up, maintaining a neutral spine. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Straight Raises on Incline Bench
exercises.hint: Place a bar on the ground behind the head of an incline bench.

exercises.name: Stride Jump Crossover
exercises.hint: Stand to the side of a box with your inside foot on top of it, close to the edge.

exercises.name: Sumo Deadlift
exercises.hint: Begin with a bar loaded on the ground. Approach the bar so that the bar intersects the middle of the feet. The feet should be set very wide, near the collars. Bend at the hips to grip the bar. The arms should be directly below the shoulders, inside the legs, and you can use a pronated grip, a mixed grip, or hook grip. Relax the shoulders, which in effect lengthens your arms.

exercises.name: Sumo Deadlift with Bands
exercises.hint: To deadlift with short bands, simply loop them over the bar before you start, and step into them to set up. Ensure that they under the back half of your foot, directly where you are driving into the floor.

exercises.name: Sumo Deadlift with Chains
exercises.hint: You can attach the chains to the sleeves of the bar, or just drape the middle over the bar so there is a greater weight increase as you lift. Attempt to keep the ends of the chains away from the plates so you don't hit them when you lower the weight.

exercises.name: Superman
exercises.hint: To begin, lie straight and face down on the floor or exercise mat. Your arms should be fully extended in front of you. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Supine Chest Throw
exercises.hint: This drill is great for chest passes when you lack a partner or a wall of sufficient strength. Lay on the ground on your back with your knees bent.

exercises.name: Supine One-Arm Overhead Throw
exercises.hint: Lay on the ground on your back with your knees bent. Hold the ball with one hand, extending the arm fully behind your head. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Supine Two-Arm Overhead Throw
exercises.hint: Lay on the ground on your back with your knees bent.

exercises.name: Suspended Fallout
exercises.hint: Adjust the straps so the handles are at an appropriate height, below waist level.

exercises.name: Suspended Push-Up
exercises.hint: Anchor your suspension straps securely to the top of a rack or other object.

exercises.name: Suspended Reverse Crunch
exercises.hint: Secure a set of suspension straps with the handles hanging about a foot off of the ground. Move yourself into a pushup plank position facing away from the rack.

exercises.name: Suspended Row
exercises.hint: Suspend your straps at around chest height. Take a handle in each hand and lean back. Keep your body erect and your head and chest up. Your arms should be fully extended. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Suspended Split Squat
exercises.hint: Suspend your straps so the handles are 18-30 inches from the floor.

exercises.name: Svend Press
exercises.hint: Begin in a standing position.

exercises.name: T-Bar Row with Handle
exercises.hint: Position a bar into a landmine or in a corner to keep it from moving. Load an appropriate weight onto your end.

exercises.name: The Straddle
exercises.hint: Begin in a seated, upright position. Start by extending your legs in front of you in a V.

exercises.name: Thigh Abductor
exercises.hint: To begin, sit down on the abductor machine and select a weight you are comfortable with. When your legs are positioned properly, grip the handles on each side. Your entire upper body (from the waist up) should be stationary. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Thigh Adductor
exercises.hint: To begin, sit down on the adductor machine and select a weight you are comfortable with. When your legs are positioned properly on the leg pads of the machine, grip the handles on each side. Your entire upper body (from the waist up) should be stationary. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Tire Flip
exercises.hint: Begin by gripping the bottom of the tire on the tread, and position your feet back a bit. Your chest should be driving into the tire.

exercises.name: Toe Touchers
exercises.hint: To begin, lie down on the floor or an exercise mat with your back pressed against the floor. Your arms should be lying across your sides with the palms facing down.

exercises.name: Torso Rotation
exercises.hint: Stand upright holding an exercise ball with both hands. Extend your arms so the ball is straight out in front of you. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Trail Running/Walking
exercises.hint: Running or hiking on trails will get the blood pumping and heart beating almost immediately. Make sure you have good shoes. While you use the muscles in your calves and buttocks to pull yourself up a hill, the knees, joints and ankles absorb the bulk of the pounding coming back down. Take smaller steps as you walk downhill, keep your knees bent to reduce the impact and slow down to avoid falling.

exercises.name: Trap Bar Deadlift
exercises.hint: For this exercise load a trap bar, also known as a hex bar, to an appropriate weight resting on the ground. Stand in the center of the apparatus and grasp both handles.

exercises.name: Tricep Dumbbell Kickback
exercises.hint: Start with a dumbbell in each hand and your palms facing your torso. Keep your back straight with a slight bend in the knees and bend forward at the waist. Your torso should be almost parallel to the floor. Make sure to keep your head up. Your upper arms should be close to your torso and parallel to the floor. Your forearms should be pointed towards the floor as you hold the weights. There should be a 90-degree angle formed between your forearm and upper arm. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Tricep Side Stretch
exercises.hint: Bring right arm across your body and over your left shoulder, holding your elbow with your left hand, until you feel a stretch in your tricep. Then repeat for your other arm.

exercises.name: Triceps Pushdown
exercises.hint: Attach a straight or angled bar to a high pulley and grab with an overhand grip (palms facing down) at shoulder width.

exercises.name: Triceps Pushdown - Rope Attachment
exercises.hint: Attach a rope attachment to a high pulley and grab with a neutral grip (palms facing each other).

exercises.name: Triceps Pushdown - V-Bar Attachment
exercises.hint: Attach a V-Bar to a high pulley and grab with an overhand grip (palms facing down) at shoulder width.

exercises.name: Triceps Stretch
exercises.hint: Reach your hand behind your head, grasp your elbow and gently pull. Hold for 10 to 20 seconds, then switch sides.

exercises.name: Tuck Crunch
exercises.hint: To begin, lie down on the floor or an exercise mat with your back pressed against the floor. Your arms should be lying across your sides with the palms facing down.

exercises.name: Two-Arm Dumbbell Preacher Curl
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell with each arm and place the upper arms on top of the preacher bench or the incline bench. The dumbbell should be held at shoulder length. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Two-Arm Kettlebell Clean
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells between your feet. To get in the starting position, push your butt back and look straight ahead.

exercises.name: Two-Arm Kettlebell Jerk
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders. Clean the kettlebells to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you swing the kettlebells towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrists as you do so, so that the palms face forward. Squat down a few inches and reverse the motion rapidly driving both kettlebells overhead. Immediately after the initial push, squat down again and get under the kettlebells. Once the kettlebells are locked out, stand upright to complete the exercise.

exercises.name: Two-Arm Kettlebell Military Press
exercises.hint: Clean two kettlebells to your shoulders. Clean the kettlebells to your shoulders by extending through the legs and hips as you swing the kettlebells towards your shoulders. Rotate your wrists as you do so, so that the palms face forward.

exercises.name: Two-Arm Kettlebell Row
exercises.hint: Place two kettlebells in front of your feet. Bend your knees slightly and then push your butt out as much as possible as you bend over to get in the starting position.

exercises.name: Underhand Cable Pulldowns
exercises.hint: Sit down on a pull-down machine with a wide bar attached to the top pulley. Adjust the knee pad of the machine to fit your height. These pads will prevent your body from being raised by the resistance attached to the bar.

exercises.name: Upper Back-Leg Grab
exercises.hint: While seated, bend forward to hug your thighs from underneath with both arms.

exercises.name: Upper Back Stretch
exercises.hint: Clasp fingers together with your thumbs pointing down, round your shoulders as you reach your hands forward.

exercises.name: Upright Barbell Row
exercises.hint: Grasp a barbell with an overhand grip that is slightly less than shoulder width. The bar should be resting on the top of your thighs with your arms extended and a slight bend in your elbows. Your back should also be straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Upright Cable Row
exercises.hint: Grasp a straight bar cable attachment that is attached to a low pulley with a pronated (palms facing your thighs) grip that is slightly less than shoulder width. The bar should be resting on top of your thighs. Your arms should be extended with a slight bend at the elbows and your back should be straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Upright Row - With Bands
exercises.hint: To begin, stand on an exercise band so that tension begins at arm's length. Grasp the handles using a pronated (palms facing your thighs) grip that is slightly less than shoulder width. The handles should be resting on top of your thighs. Your arms should be extended with a slight bend at the elbows and your back should be straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Upward Stretch
exercises.hint: Extend both hands straight above your head, palms touching.

exercises.name: V-Bar Pulldown
exercises.hint: Sit down on a pull-down machine with a V-Bar attached to the top pulley.

exercises.name: V-Bar Pullup
exercises.hint: Start by placing the middle of the V-bar in the middle of the pull-up bar (assuming that the pull-up station you are using does not have neutral grip handles). The V-Bar handles will be facing down so that you can hang from the pull-up bar through the use of the handles.

exercises.name: Vertical Swing
exercises.hint: Allow the dumbbell to hang at arms length between your legs, holding it with both hands. Keep your back straight and your head up.

exercises.name: Walking, Treadmill
exercises.hint: To begin, step onto the treadmill and select the desired option from the menu. Most treadmills have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout.

exercises.name: Weighted Ball Hyperextension
exercises.hint: To begin, lie down on an exercise ball with your torso pressing against the ball and parallel to the floor. The ball of your feet should be pressed against the floor to help keep you balanced. Place a weighted plate under your chin or behind your neck. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Weighted Ball Side Bend
exercises.hint: To begin, lie down on an exercise ball with your left side of the torso (waist, hips and shoulder) pressed against the ball.

exercises.name: Weighted Bench Dip
exercises.hint: For this exercise you will need to place a bench behind your back and another one in front of you. With the benches perpendicular to your body, hold on to one bench on its edge with the hands close to your body, separated at shoulder width. Your arms should be fully extended.

exercises.name: Weighted Crunches
exercises.hint: Lie flat on your back with your feet flat on the ground or resting on a bench with your knees bent at a 90 degree angle.

exercises.name: Weighted Jump Squat
exercises.hint: Position a lightly loaded barbell across the back of your shoulders. You could also use a weighted vest, sandbag, or other type of resistance for this exercise.

exercises.name: Weighted Pull Ups
exercises.hint: Attach a weight to a dip belt and secure it around your waist. Grab the pull-up bar with the palms of your hands facing forward. For a medium grip, your hands should be spaced at shoulder width. Both arms should be extended in front of you holding the bar at the chosen grip.

exercises.name: Weighted Sissy Squat
exercises.hint: Standing upright, with feet at shoulder width and toes raised, use one hand to hold onto the beams of a squat rack and the opposite arm to hold a plate on top of your chest. This is your starting position.

exercises.name: Weighted Sit-Ups - With Bands
exercises.hint: Start out by strapping the bands around the base of the decline bench. Place the handles towards the inside of the decline bench so that when lying down, you can reach for both of them.

exercises.name: Weighted Squat
exercises.hint: Start by positioning two flat benches shoulder width apart from each other. Stand on top of them and wrap the weighted belt around your waist with the amount of weight you feel comfortable with. Make sure your toes are facing out.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Barbell Bench Press
exercises.hint: Lie back on a flat bench with feet firm on the floor. Using a wide, pronated (palms forward) grip that is around 3 inches away from shoulder width (for each hand), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. The bar will be perpendicular to the torso and the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Decline Barbell Bench Press
exercises.hint: Lie back on a decline bench with the feet securely locked at the front of the bench. Using a wide, pronated (palms forward) grip that is around 3 inches away from shoulder width (for each hand), lift the bar from the rack and hold it straight over you with your arms locked. The bar will be perpendicular to the torso and the floor. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Decline Barbell Pullover
exercises.hint: Lie down on a decline bench with both legs securely locked in position. Reach for the barbell behind the head using a pronated grip (palms facing out). Make sure to grab the barbell wider than shoulder width apart for this exercise. Slowly lift the barbell up from the floor by using your arms.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Lat Pulldown
exercises.hint: Sit down on a pull-down machine with a wide bar attached to the top pulley. Make sure that you adjust the knee pad of the machine to fit your height. These pads will prevent your body from being raised by the resistance attached to the bar.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Pulldown Behind The Neck
exercises.hint: Sit down on a pull-down machine with a wide bar attached to the top pulley. Make sure that you adjust the knee pad of the machine to fit your height. These pads will prevent your body from being raised by the resistance attached to the bar.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Rear Pull-Up
exercises.hint: Grab the pull-up bar with the palms facing forward using a wide grip.

exercises.name: Wide-Grip Standing Barbell Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright while holding a barbell at the wide outer handle. The palm of your hands should be facing forward. The elbows should be close to the torso. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Wide Stance Barbell Squat
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.

exercises.name: Wide Stance Stiff Legs
exercises.hint: Begin with a barbell loaded on the floor. Adopt a wide stance, and then bend at the hips to grab the bar. Your hips should be as far back as possible, and your legs nearly straight. Keep your back straight, and your head and chest up. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Wind Sprints
exercises.hint: Hang from a pull-up bar using a pronated grip. Your arms and legs should be extended. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Windmills
exercises.hint: Lie on your back with your arms extended out to the sides and your legs straight. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: World's Greatest Stretch
exercises.hint: This is a three-part stretch. Begin by lunging forward, with your front foot flat on the ground and on the toes of your back foot. With your knees bent, squat down until your knee is almost touching the ground. Keep your torso erect, and hold this position for 10-20 seconds.

exercises.name: Wrist Circles
exercises.hint: Start by standing straight with your feet being shoulder width apart from each other. Elevate your arms to the side of you until they are fully extended and parallel to the floor at a height that is evenly aligned with your shoulders. Tip: Your torso and arms should form the letter "T: Your palms should be facing down. This is the starting position.

exercises.name: Wrist Roller
exercises.hint: To begin, stand straight up grabbing a wrist roller using a pronated grip (palms facing down). Your feet should be shoulder width apart.

exercises.name: Wrist Rotations with Straight Bar
exercises.hint: Hold a barbell with both hands and your palms facing down; hands spaced about shoulder width. This will be your starting position.

exercises.name: Yoke Walk
exercises.hint: The yoke is usually done with a yoke apparatus, but is sometimes seen with refrigerators or other heavy objects.

exercises.name: Zercher Squats
exercises.hint: This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes. To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height. The correct height should be anywhere above the waist but below the chest. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, lock your hands together and place the bar on top of your arms in between the forearm and upper arm.

exercises.name: Zottman Curl
exercises.hint: Stand up with your torso upright and a dumbbell in each hand being held at arms length. The elbows should be close to the torso.

exercises.name: Zottman Preacher Curl
exercises.hint: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and place your upper arms on top of the preacher bench or the incline bench. The dumbbells should be held at shoulder height and the elbows should be flexed. Hold the dumbbells with the palms of your hands facing down. This will be your starting position.
